  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A child throws a ball toward the front end of an approaching train. The collision between the ball and the train is perfectly elastic. Let 𝑣 be the speed of the ball with respect to the train and 𝑉 its speed with respect to the ground. If the labels“ i” and “f” refer to those speeds just before and just after, respectively, the ball hits the train, then',
  '["𝑣𝑖 = 𝑣𝑓 𝑎𝑛𝑑 𝑉𝑖 < 𝑉𝑓","𝑣𝑖 < 𝑣𝑓 𝑎𝑛𝑑 𝑉𝑖 < 𝑉𝑓","𝑣𝑖 > 𝑣𝑓 𝑎𝑛𝑑 𝑉𝑖 < 𝑉𝑓","𝑣𝑖 = 𝑣𝑓 𝑎𝑛𝑑 𝑉𝑖 > 𝑉𝑓"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Let us first solve in the ground frame: Vi + Ui = Vf + Uf U = V elocity of train. Using the elastic collision fact one finds: Vi −Ui = −(Vf −Uf) Thus, Vf ≈−Vi + Ui + Uf Thus, Vf > Vi Now switch to relative frame, vi = Vi −Ui vf = Vf −Uf from elastic collision one finds: Vi −Ui = −(Vf −Uf) vi = −vf Thus, |vi| = |vf| There can also be alternative methods which I didn’t know.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-50', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  50, '50', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A physics textbook of mass m rests flat on a horizontal table of mass M placed on the ground. Let Na→b be the contact force exerted by body “a” on body “b”. According to Newton’s 3rd Law, which of the following is an action-reaction pair of forces?',
  '["mg and Ntable→book","(m + M )g and Ntable→book","Nground→table and Mg + Nbook→table","Nground→table and Ntable→ground"]'::jsonb, 3, 'This is one the conceptual question from Newton’s 3rd Law: ”For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.” ⃗FAB = −⃗FBA In Option A: Earth pulls the book down with mg, In response the book pulls the earth. So the normal isn’t the third law Force. In Option B: The combined weight of the table is being pulled down by the Earth, In response the combined mass pulls Earth up or (towards the table). In Option C: Two forces adding wouldn’t make the reaction Force.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-51', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  51, '51', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A simple pendulum of length L with a bob of mass m is taken into Earth orbit on the International Space Station. Its frequency of oscillation with respect to that on the ground is',
  '["greater","smaller but non- zero","the same","zero"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A simple pendulum frequency relies on gravity: ω = r g L Aboard the International Space Station both the bob and the support are in (near-)free-fall, so the local effective gravitational acceleration geff is zero.',
