),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-52', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  52, '52', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A projectile is launched with an initial velocity 𝑣𝑖, with 𝑣𝑖𝑥 and 𝑣𝑖𝑦 the horizontal and vertical velocity components, respectively. When is there a point on its trajectory after launch where its velocity is perpendicular to its acceleration?',
  '["Always","Only if 𝑣𝑖𝑥 ≠ 0 and 𝑣𝑖𝑦 points upward","Only if 𝑣𝑖𝑥 ≠ 0","Always, except if 𝑣𝑖𝑥 = 0"]'::jsonb, 1, 'For ideal projectile motion the velocity components at time t are v(t) =  vix, viy −gt   , vi =  vix, viy   . The two velocity vectors are perpendicular when their dot product is zero: v(t) · vi = v2 ix + viy  viy −gt   = 0. Solving for t gives t = v2 ix + v2 iy g viy . • A positive time requires viy > 0, so the projectile must be launched with an upward vertical component. • We also need vix ̸= 0. If vix = 0, then t = viy/g corresponds to the instant when v(t) = 0 (the top of straight–up flight), and the zero vector has no direction to be perpendicular to.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-53', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  53, '53', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'As more and more negative electric charge is being brought to a conducting sphere, inside the sphere',
  '["The electric field and potential increase","The electric field stays constant and the potential. increases","The electric field stays constant and the potential. decreases","The electric field increases and the potential decreases"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Since the Options are glitched out here’s what they say: (a) The electric field and potential increase. (b) The electric field stays constant and the potential increases (c) The electric field stays constant and the potential decreases (d) The electric field increases and the potential decreases Gauss law tells us: Z ⃗E · d⃗a = Qenclosed ϵ0 In a conducting sphere all charge resides on the surface thus Electric field is zero inside. As Q becomes more negative, V becomes a larger-magnitude negative number—i.e. its numerical value decreases.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-54', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  54, '54', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A string of length L is composed of two segments of equal length. One segment has linear mass density 𝜇1 and the other 𝜇2 ≠ 𝜇1. One segment is tied to a wall, and the string is stretched by a force, applied to the other segment, which is much greater than the total weight of the string. If 𝑇𝑖 is the tension in the ith segment, and 𝑣𝑖 the speed of a transverse wave propagating along that segment',
  '["𝑣1 = 𝑣2 & 𝑇1 = 𝑇2","𝑣1 ≠ 𝑣2 & 𝑇1 = 𝑇2","𝑣1 = 𝑣2 & 𝑇1 ≠ 𝑇2","𝑣1 ≠ 𝑣 2 & 𝑇1 ≠ 𝑇2"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Because the stretching force F is assumed much greater than the weight of the string, the static load is transmitted essentially undiminished along the whole length. Hence T1 = T2 = F. For a stretched string the transverse-wave speed is v = s T µ . With the same tension T but different linear mass densities, v1 = s T µ1 , v2 = s T µ2 . Since µ1 ̸= µ2, we must have v1 ̸= v2. Therefore v1 ̸= v2 & T1 = T2.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-55', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  55, '55', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A perfectly straight portion of a uniform rope has mass M and length L. At end A of the segment, the tension in the rope is TA; at end B it is TB > TA. The tension in the rope at a distance L/5 from end A is',
  '["TB − TA","(TA + TB)/5","(4TA + TB)/5","(TA − TB)/ 5"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Since TB > TA there will be a net force given by: TB −TA = Ma (1) Now at a distance L/5 the net force will be: T −TA = M L × L 5 × a (2) Because of the same acceleration compare the two equations and solve for T: T −TA = M 5 × TB −TA M T = TB −TA + TA = 4TA + TB',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-56', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  56, '56', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'Two spheres are identical except that sphere A is white whereas sphere B is black. After they have been in thermal contact long enough with each other and their surroundings, in the visible range',
  '["A radiates less than B","Both emit the same amount of radiation","A radiates more than B","A radiates more than B only if its temperature is high enough"]'::jsonb, 0, 'After a long time in thermal contact with each other and their surroundings, both spheres reach the same equilibrium temperature T. For any surface at temperature T, the radiant power emitted per unit area is given by the Stefan–Boltzmann law, Pemit = εσT 4, with εwhite < εblack. Hence P white emit < P black emit . Each sphere remains in energy balance (net heat flow = 0) because it absorbs radiation in proportion to the same emissivity. The black sphere both absorbs and emits more strongly than the white one, so in the visible range sphere A (white) radiates less than sphere B (black).',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
