(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-58', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  58, '58', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A glass-walled elevator is moving upwards with constant acceleration. At some point in the elevator’s motion, a bolt breaks loose and drops from the ceiling. What is the motion of the bolt as seen by an external observer (i.e. one located outside the elevator)?',
  '["The bolt moves upwards at a constant speed","The bold initially moves upwards, then slows, reverses direction and moves downwards","The bolt appears to remain stationary","The bolt immediately moves downwards, accelerating as it goes"]'::jsonb, 1, 'External (inertial) observer • Initial state. When the bolt breaks loose (t = 0) it keeps the car’s upward speed v0. • Forces. After detachment the only force is its weight mg, so the acceleration is a = −g (downward). • Kinematics (with +y upward). v(t) = v0 −g t, y(t) = v0 t −1 2gt2. • Turning point. It rises until v = 0 at ttop = v0 g , ymax = v2 2g. After that it accelerates downward with magnitude g. Thus the bolt first moves upward, momentarily stops, then reverses and falls.',
  7, '/api/storage/paper-assets/physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924/figures/q58-p7-1.webp', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-59', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  59, '59', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'The Earth and the Moon both exert gravitational forces on objects in their vicinity. Imagine a line joining the Earth to the Moon, and extending to either side, as shown below (not to scale). Consider placing an object along this line. Where along this line is the net gravitational force on the object due to the Earth and the Moon equal to zero.',
  '["On the far side of the Earth from the Moon","Halfway between the Earth and the Moon","Between the Earth and the Moon, but closer to the Earth than to the Moon","Between the Earth and the Moon, but closer to the Moon than to the Earth"]'::jsonb, 3, 'A mass m experiences the gravitational attraction by a greater mass M given as: Fg = GMm r2 Now since mass M of moon is smaller to increase the magnitude of the total force by the moon Fm the distance from it r must decrease i.e nearer to moon. Nearer to moon automatically means farther from Earth in this case. Thus option D',
  7, '/api/storage/paper-assets/physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924/figures/q59-p7-2.webp', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-60', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  60, '60', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A ball is held at a height H above a floor, as sketched in the diagram on the right. It is then released and falls to the floor. If air resistance can be ignored, which of the four graphs below (labelled a to d) correctly gives the mechanical energy Emech of the Earth-ball system as a function of the altitude y of the ball?',
  '["Diagram A","Diagram B","Diagram C","Diagram D"]'::jsonb, 1, 'This problem is simple: Use energy conservation.',
  7, '/api/storage/paper-assets/physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924/figures/q60-p7-6.webp', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-61', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  61, '61', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'Some students are doing an experiment to calculate the spring constant of a particular spring. As part of this experiment, they suspend an object from the spring, pull it downwards, and let it go. The object then oscillates up and down, with a period of about 2 seconds. The students use a stopwatch to measure the period of oscillation. The best way to get an accurate and precise measurement of the period would be to',
  '["Measure the time taken for a single oscillation 10 times, and average the results","Measure the time taken for a single oscillation 10 times, and average the results. Repeat this measurement three times, and average the results","Measure the time taken for 10 oscillations, and divide by 10. Repeat this measurement three times, and average the results","All of the methods above are equivalent, and will result in the same precision in the measurement of the period of oscillation"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Key source of error is with a hand-held stopwatch the dominant uncertainty is the human reaction time ∆trxn ∼0.1–0.2 s, which contaminates both the start and stop clicks. (a) 10 separate timings of one oscillation ⇒σT ∝ √ 10 ∆trxn. (b) Same as (a) but repeated three times (total 30 readings) ⇒better statistics, yet every single-cycle timing still carries two reaction-time errors. (c) 3 separate timings of 10 oscillations each, then divide by 10 ⇒each raw measurement has only two reaction-time errors spread over 10 periods, so the fractional uncertainty per period is reduced by a factor 10. Averaging the three runs further lowers the random error  σT ∝ √ 2 ∆trxn √   . (d) Claims all methods are equivalent – contradicted by the analysis above....',
  8, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-62', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  62, '62', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A roller-coaster car is full of water, and is moving at constant velocity along a frictionless horizontal track. Someone removes a plug in the bottom of the floor, allowing the water to drain out. Ignoring air resistance, as the water drains out the car will',
  '["Slow down","Continue to move at constant velocity","Speed up","Initially speed up, then slow down"]'::jsonb, 1, 'With the track frictionless, the net external horizontal force on the system is zero. When the plug is removed the water exits vertically downward, so the horizontal momentum of the car–water system is conserved: (mcar + mwater)v0 = mcar v(t) + mwaterv0 so v(t) = v0. Hence the car continues at its original constant velocity.',
  8, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-63', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  63, '63', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'The velocity of a particle moving along the x-axis changes from vi to vf . For which of these values of 𝑣𝑖and 𝑣𝑓 does the particle’s kinetic energy increase the most?',
  '["𝑣𝑖 = 5 𝑚/𝑠 & 𝑣𝑓 = 2 𝑚/𝑠","𝑣𝑖 = 5 𝑚/𝑠 & 𝑣𝑓 = −2 𝑚/𝑠","𝑣𝑖 = −5 𝑚/𝑠 & 𝑣𝑓 = −2 𝑚/𝑠","𝑣𝑖 = 2 𝑚/𝑠 & 𝑣𝑓 = −5 𝑚/𝑠"]'::jsonb, 3, 'The kinetic energy change is ∆K = 2m  v 2 f −v 2 i   , so only the squares of the speeds matter. Option ∆K ∝v 2 f −v 2 i (a) 22 −52 = 4 −25 = −21 (b) (−2)2 −52 = 4 −25 = −21 (c) (−2)2 −(−5)2 = 4 −25 = −21 (d) (−5)2 −22 = 25 −4 = 21 The largest increase (∆K > 0) occurs for option (d): vi = 2 m/s and vf = −5 m/s.',
  8, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-64', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  64, '64', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'An introductory physics student, elated by a first semester grade, celebrates by dropping a textbook from a balcony into a deep layer of soft snow which is 3.00 m below. Upon hitting the snow the book sinks a further 1.00 m into it before coming to a stop. The mass of the book is 5.0 kg. Assuming a constant retarding force, what is the approximate value of force from the snow on the book?',
  '["100 N","120 N","150 N","200 N"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Energy lost in the whole drop equals work done by the snow’s upward force: mg(3.0 + 1.0) = F (1.0). Plug in m = 5.0 kg and g ≈9.8 m/s2: F ≈5.0 × 9.8 × 4 = 2.0 × 102 N.',
  8, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-65', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  65, '65', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A mass on a frictionless table is attached to the midpoint of an originally unstretched spring fixed at the ends. If the mass is displaced a distance A parallel to the table surface but perpendicular to the spring, it exhibits oscillations. The period T of the oscillations',
  '["Does not depend on A","Increases as A increases, approaching a fixed value","Decreases as A increases, approaching a fixed value","Is approximately constant for small values of A, then increases without bound"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Suppose the springs have equilibrium length l and spring constant k. If we displace the mass m by a distance x parallel to the springs, the force in each spring is F = k ∆l = k  p l2 + x2 −l   . Hence the net restoring force on the mass is Fr = −2F cos θ = −2k  p l2 + x2 −l   x √ l2 + x2 = −2kx   1 − l √ l2 + x2   . For any finite x, the magnitude of Fr is smaller than the simple-harmonic estimate FSHM = −2kx; consequently the acceleration is smaller and the oscillation period T is longer than the SHM period TSHM = 2π r m 2k . As x →∞we have Fr →FSHM, so T →TSHM. Since T > TSHM for small displacements and decreases monotonically toward TSHM as x grows, the period T decreases with increasing amplitude. Thus the answer is C . Credit to : KEVINSHUANG FOR THIS SOLUTION',
  8, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-66', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  66, '66', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'Kepler''s Laws state that 1 the orbits of planets are elliptical with one focus at the sun, II. a line connecting the sun and a planet sweeps out equal areas in equal times, and III. the square of the period of a planet''s orbit is proportional to the cube of its semimajor axis. Which of these laws would remain true if the force of gravity were proportional to 1/r3 rather than 1/r2?',
  '["Only I","Only II","Only III","Both II and III"]'::jsonb, 1, 'This can be solved without having to do any math: Option A : It can’t be this due to the fact elliptical orbits have a squared term in them which would not remain the same once cubed. Option C: This is obvious since changing r changes the semi-major axis. Option D: We just ruled out C so it wouldn’t make sense.',
  8, '/api/storage/paper-assets/physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924/figures/q66-p8-1.webp', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-67', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  67, '67', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'Two blocks are suspended by two massless elastic strings to the ceiling as shown in the figure. The masses of the upper and lower block are m 1 = 2 kg and m 2 = 4 kg, respectively. If the upper string is suddenly cut just above the top block what are the accelerations of the two blocks at the moment when the top block begins to fall?',
  '["Upper: 10 m/s2; lower: 0","Upper: 10 m/s2; lower: 10 m/s2","Upper: 20 m/s2; lower: 10 m/s2","Upper: 30 m/s2; lower: 0"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Immediately after the upper string is cut the lower (elastic, but massless) string has had no time to change its length so its tension is the same as it was a moment earlier. Because forces can only change after information travels through the string, the cut has not yet been “felt” at the lower block. block forces just after the cut (upward +) m1 = 2 kg (−T) + (−m1g) m2 = 4 kg +T −m2g Originally the system was static, so the tension in the lower string was T = m2g = 4 kg (10 m/s2) = 40 N. Acceleration of the upper block For m1 do the greater force mius the less force = ma): = −T −m1g = −  40 + 20   N = −60 N = m1a1 Hence a1 = P Fm1 m1 = −60 = −30 m/s2. (The minus sign simply means the acceleration is downward.) Thus the top block initially accelerates downward at 30 m/s2 Acceleration of the lower block For m2 the upward tension balances its weight: +T −m2g = 40 −40 = 0 =⇒ a2 = 0....',
  8, '/api/storage/paper-assets/physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924/figures/q67-p8-manual.webp', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-68', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  68, '68', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A ball rolls from the back of a large truck traveling 10.0 m/s to the right. The ball is traveling horizontally at 8.0 m/s to the left relative to an observer in the truck. The ball lands on the roadway 1.25 m below its starting level. How far behind the truck does it land?',
  '["0.50 m","1.0 m","4.0 m","5.0 m"]'::jsonb, 2, 'First we find the velocity of the ball relative to the ground: Vball from truck = Vball,ground −Vtruck,ground Vball,ground = −8 + 10 = 2 m/s Where the minus sign is for moving left. Now find the time it took to fall down: Sy = +1 2(g)(t2) t = s 2Sy g = r 2(1.25) 9.8 ≈0.5 s Use this time to see how much both the truck and the ball moved horizontally: Sx,truck = v × t = 10 × 0.5 = 5 m Sx,ball = v × t = 2 × 0.5 = 1 m Hence to find out how far behind the ball is: ∆S = 5 −1 = 4 m',
  8, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-69', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  69, '69', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'A block foats partially submerged in a container of liquid. When the entire container is accelerated upward, which of the following happens? Assume that both the liquid and the block are incompressible.',
  '["The block descends down lower into the liquid","The block ascends up higher in the liquid","The block does not ascend nor descend in the liquid","The answer depends on the rate of change of the acceleration"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let us first consider without acceleration, From Archimedes principle: Mg = ρV g The weight and the buoyant force balance each other. Now consider the acceleration within the frame of the block, The new acceleration you feel is: geff = (g + a) But noticing the forces on the block: Mgeff = ρV geff The two still balance thus the block doesn’t sink or ascend.',
  9, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-ii-70', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  70, '70', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'An object is released from rest and falls a distance h during the first second of time. How far will it fall during the next second of time?',
  '["h","2h","3h","4h"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Let the object be released from rest at t = 0 and fall with constant acceleration g. The distance fallen in the first second is given to be h: h = s(1) = 1 2g(1)2 =⇒ g = 2h. The total distance fallen in the first two seconds is s(2) = 1 2g(2)2 = 1 2(2h) (4) = 4h. Hence the additional distance covered during just the second second is ∆s = s(2) −s(1) = 4h −h = 3h. The object falls 3h. PART-3 Given: Mass(m) = 0.20 kg Extension(x0) = 0.16 m',
  9, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-iii-1', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  1, 'Descriptive 1', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'Question No 1: A 0.20 kg mass is attached to the lower end of a helical spring which is fixed at its upper end. The vertical spring is extended by 0.16 m in equilibrium. Determine: a) The change in gravitational potential energy of the mass due to spring’s extension. b) The elastic energy stored in the spring. c) Why do the magnitude of (i) and (ii) differ? The mass is pulled down a further distance of 0.07 m and released. d) What is its kinetic energy when passing through the equilibrium position? e) What is its period of oscillation? f) If the upper end of the spring is released, describe the motion of the mass and the spring? (10)',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'At equillbrium: k = mg x0 = 0.20 × 9.81 0.16 ≈12.26 N/m . A) The change in GPE: Consider the zero of GPE at x=0 so when the mass moves down by x0, ∆Ug = −mg x0 = −0.20 × 9.81 × 0.16 ≈−0.31 J . (It loses 0.31J of gravitational potential.) B) Elastic energy stored in the spring. Taken Zero of spring potential again at x=0 Us = 1 2 k x2 0 = 1 2 × 12.26 × (0.16)2 ≈0.16 J . C) Why the magnitudes differ: Lowering the mass slowly to equilibrium does work mgx0 against gravity, but the spring force increases linearly from 0 to mg. The energy stored is the area under the F–x curve, 1 2 (mg) x0, so only half of the gravitational work becomes spring energy; the rest is dissipated. Now pull the mass a further A = 0.07 m below equilibrium and release D) Kinetic energy at equilibrium: Choose the zero of total potential energy at the spring’s natural length x = 0, with x measured downward. Then the total potential energy is U(x) = Us + Ug = 2kx2 −mgx. 1. Evaluate at the equilibrium point x = x0 (where kx0 = mg): U1 = U(x0) = 1 2 k x2 0 −mg x0. 2. Evaluate at the lowest point x = x0 + A: U2 = U(x0 + A) = 1 2 k (x0 + A)2 −mg (x0 + A). 3. Compute the change in potential energy as the mass moves from the low point back to equilibrium: ∆U = Ufinal −Uinitial = U1 −U2. Substituting and simplifying (using kx0 = mg) gives ∆U = −1 2 k A2. 4. By conservation of mechanical energy, ∆K = −∆U , so the kinetic energy at equilibrium is Keq = −  −1 2 k A2  = 1 2 k A2. K = 1 2 k A2 = 1 2 × 12.26 × (0.07)2 ≈0.03 J . E) Period of oscillation. T = 2π rm k = 2π r 0.20 12.26 ≈0.80 s . F) Motion if the upper end is released. Once the support is released, the mass and spring fall together under gravity. In free–fall the equilibrium extension remains x0, so there is no net restoring force to drive oscillations....',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924-part-iii-2', 'published', 'physics-2023-final-physics-2023-ac5a924', 'Physics',
  2, 'Descriptive 2', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2023, 'NSTC 2023 Physics Paper', 'Question No 2: a) Assuming the planets are in circular motion around the Sun, with radius 𝑅 and period 𝑇, use the data in Table 2.1 to test, graphically, the hypothesis that T is proportional to 𝑅𝛼 , where 𝛼 is a constant. Obtain from the graph: i) A value for 𝛼 and give its accuracy. ii) The constant of proportionality in SI units. PLANET R/108 km T/days Earth 1.49 365 Mars 2.28 687 Jupiter 7.78 4333 Uranus 28.7 30690 Table 2.1 b) i) Derive, using mechanics, the relationship between T and R in terms of the mass of the Sun, MS. ii) Determine MS using the data in (a). iii) The distance of the Moon from the Earth is 3.8 x 10^5 km and its period is 27.3 days. Deduce the ratio (MS/ME), where ME is the mass of the Earth. (10+10)',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'A (1) A value for α and give its accuracy. Plug any two values from the given data in Equation (1): (365) = k × (1.49 × 108)α ...(i) (687) = k × (2.28 × 108)α ...(ii) Divide (i) and (ii): 687 = k × (1.49 × 108)α k × (2.28 × 108)α 687 = (149 228)α Taking Natural Log on both sides: ln (149 228)α = ln 365 α × ln (149 228) = ln 365 α = ln 365 687/ ln (149 228) ≈1.48 To find the accuracy/uncertainty, do this for either one more value, I will pick Earth–Uranus for which doing the same as above gives: αEU ≈1.50 Midpoint and half-range: α = 1.50 + 1.48 = 1.49 ∆α = 1.50 −1.48 = 0.01 So you can write your answer now as: α = 1.49 ± 0.01 A (2) The constant of proportionality k in SI units: Plug you α value in equation (i) converted in SI: (365 × 24 × 60 × 60) = k × (1.49 × 108 × 103)1.49 k = (365 × 86400) (1.49 × 1011)1.50 k ≈5.48 × 10−10 s · m−1.5 B (1) Derive, using mechanics, the relationship between T and R in terms of the mass of the Sun, Ms: Consider a planet of mass m with a speed v orbiting at distance R from the Sun. Thus, the centripetal force and the Gravitational force will be equal: mv2 R = GMsm R2 v2 = GMs R We also know that in a circular orbit: S = v × T v = 2πR T Plug this: (2πR T )2 = GMs R Simplifying one finds: T = s 4π2 GMs × R1.5 B (2) Determine Ms using the data in (a): Comparing the two equations we find that: k = s 4π2 GMs Rearranging and simplifying: Ms = 4π2 Gk2 k ≈5.48 × 10−10, G ≈6.67 × 10−11, π ≈3.14 Ms = 4(3.14)2 (6.67 × 10−11)(5.48 × 10−10)2 Ms ≈1.97 × 1030 kg B (3) The distance of the Moon from the Earth is 3.8 × 105 km and its period is 27.3 days. Deduce the ratio (MS/ME), where ME is the mass of the Earth. Using the same relation find mass of the Earth: T = s 4π2 GME × R3/2 ME = 4π2R3 G × T 2 Again plugging in (SI Units), ME = 4 × (3.14)2 × (3....',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
