(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-21', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  21, '21', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a car starts moving from rest with acceleration 𝑎 = 10.0 𝑚/𝑠2, then continues uniformly, and finally stops with deceleration at the same rate a. Assume that the time taken for the whole journey is 40 s with an average velocity of 100 km/hour. What is the duration of the uniform motion?',
  '["32 s","34 s","30 s","35 s"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q21: (b) 34 s Solution. Let the car accelerate from rest at rate a = 10 m s−2 for a time t1, move with constant speed v for t2, and decelerate at the same magnitude a for another t1. 2t1 + t2 = 40 s (1) During each constant–acceleration stage, v = at1, sacc = 1 2at2 1. Because the deceleration stage is symmetric, the total distance is S = 2sacc + vt2 = at2 1 + vt2. The average velocity is ¯v = 100 km h−1 = 27.78 m s−1, so S = ¯v (40 s) = 1111.11 m. Substituting v = at1 and t2 from (1): at2 1 + at1(40 −2t1) = 1111.11 =⇒−10t2 1 + 400t1 −1111.11 = 0. Solving gives t1 = 3.0 s (the other root is unphysical), hence t2 = 40 −2t1 = 34 s.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-22', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  22, '22', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A particle has a radius vector which varies with time t as 𝑟⃗⃗ = (1 − 𝛽𝑡)𝑡𝑟𝑜⃗⃗⃗ , where 𝑟𝑜⃗⃗⃗ is a constant vector and 𝛽 is a positive constant factor. What is the acceleration of the particle?',
  '["−2𝛽𝑟𝑜⃗⃗⃗","2𝛽𝑟𝑜⃗⃗⃗","𝛽𝑟𝑜⃗⃗⃗","−𝛽𝑟𝑜⃗⃗⃗"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q22: (a) −2βr0 Solution. Given r(t) = r0  t −βt2  , v = dr dt = r0(1 −2βt), a = dv dt = −2βr0.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-23', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  23, '23', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Use the information in question 22. Let the particle starts at 𝑡 = 0 and returns back to its original position after time 𝛥𝑡 which is given by',
  '["𝛽","2 𝛽⁄","𝛽 2⁄","1 𝛽⁄"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q23: (d) ∆t = 1 β Solution. The particle is back at the origin when r(t) = 0: r0  t −βt2  = 0 ⇒t(t −1 β) = 0 ⇒t = 1 β (non-trivial root).',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-24', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  24, '24', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a mass slides on a horizontal frictionless track. It is connected to a spring fastened to a wall. Initially, the amplitude of the oscillations is A and the spring constant is 𝑘1. The spring constant then decreases adiabatically at a constant rate until the value 𝑘2is reached. (For example, suppose the spring is being dissolved by the nitric acid.) What is the new amplitude?',
  '["𝐴(𝑘2 𝑘1 )1 2⁄","𝐴(𝑘2 𝑘1 )1 4⁄","𝐴(𝑘1 𝑘2 )1 2⁄","𝐴(𝑘1 𝑘 2 )1 4⁄"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q24: (d) A  k1 k2  1/4 Solution. For a harmonic oscillator, energy E = 1 2kA2 and angular frequency ω = p k/m. During a quasi-static (adiabatic) change, the action J = E ω = 1 2A2√ km remains constant, so A′2p k2 = A2p k1 =⇒A′ = A  k1 k2  1/4 .',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-25', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  25, '25', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a block of mass 1.0 kg is moving with a velocity v. It collides with a block of mass 6.0 kg that is initially at rest. What is the velocity of the heavier block if the collision is perfectly elastic?',
  '["2𝑣 5⁄","3𝑣 7⁄","2𝑣 7⁄","3𝑣 5⁄"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q25: (c) 2v Solution. For a 1-D perfectly elastic collision (masses m1 = 1, m2 = 6; u2 = 0): v2 = 2m1 m1 + m2 u1 = 1 + 6 v = 2v 7 .',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-26', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  26, '26', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A particle is placed 10 cm from the center of a rough turntable. The turntable is steadily accelerated at 20 rad per squared second. When the angular velocity reaches 70 rad per second, the particle starts to slip. If the particle had originally been placed 15 cm from the center and the turntable accelerated as before, at what angular velocity would it have started to slip?',
  '["1.2 rad/s","5.4 rad/s","7.8 rad/s","10 rad/s"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q26: (b) 5.4 rad s−1 Solution. A particle sticks provided the static-friction limit is not exceeded: fmax = µmg , freq = m p (ω2r)2 + (αr)2 . Since α is unchanged, the ratio freq mr ≈ω2 dominates. Thus µ determined at (r1, ω1) satisfies µg = ω2 1r1, giving the slip criterion ω2r = ω2 1r1. Hence ω2 = ω1 rr1 r2 = 70 rad s−1 r 0.10 0.15 ≈5.4 rad s−1.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-27', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  27, '27', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a solid cylinder of uniform density having mass M and radius R. A string of length L is completely wound around the cylinder and a small weight of mass m is attached to its end. Assume the mass of the string is negligible whereas 𝑀 = 30𝑚. The mass m is released from rest under the influence of gravity. What is the velocity of the mass m when the string is entirely unwound?',
  '["√16𝑔𝐿","√8𝑔𝐿 2⁄","√𝑔𝐿 8⁄","√2𝑔𝐿"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q27: (c) v = r gL Solution. Gravitational potential mgL converts to 2mv2 + 1 2Iω2, I = 1 2MR2, ω = v R, M = 30m. Thus mgL = 1 2mv2 + 1 4Mv2 =   1 2 + 7.5   mv2 = 8mv2, so v2 = gL/8.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-28', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  28, '28', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a block of mass M sliding on a frictionless surface of ice at a uniform velocity of 20 m/s. The block reaches a rough patch on ice where the coefficient of kinetic friction is suddenly increased from 0 to 0.8. What is the distance the block slides before stopping?',
  '["23.2 m","25.5 m","28.2 m","27. 5 m"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q28: (b) 25.5 m Solution. Initial kinetic energy 1 2Mv2 is dissipated by kinetic friction: µkMgd = 1 2Mv2 =⇒d = v2 2µkg = 2(0.8)(9.8) ≈25.5 m.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-29', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  29, '29', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a spring-mass system with oscillation frequency f. What is the new frequency of the oscillator if the spring constant is halved and mass is doubled?',
  '["𝑓 2⁄","2𝑓","2.5𝑓","𝑓 4⁄"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q29: (a) f Solution. For a spring–mass oscillator f = 1 2π r k m. With k →k/2 and m →2m, f ′ = 1 2π r k/2 2m = 1 2π r k 4m = f 2.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-30', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  30, '30', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A uniform mass density cylinder of radius r and mass m rolls down a ramp of length d and height h. Assuming there is no slipping during the rolling, the speed of the cylinder at the bottom of the ramp is given by',
  '["√2𝑔𝑑","√2𝑔ℎ","√𝑔ℎ𝑟 𝑑⁄","√4𝑔ℎ 3⁄"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q30: (d) v = q 4gh Solution. For a uniform cylinder (solid) rolling without slipping: mgh = 1 2mv2 + 1 2Iω2, I = 1 2mr2, ω = v r. Therefore mgh = 1 2mv2 + 1 4mv2 = 3 4mv2 =⇒v = r 4gh 3 .',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-31', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  31, '31', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'What is the recoil velocity of a rifle of mass 5.0 kg, if a bullet of mass 0.01 kg is shot at a speed of 250 m/s?',
  '["-0.5 m/s","0.5 m/s","0.25 m/s","-0. 25 m/s"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q31: (a) −0.5 m s−1 Solution. At the instant the bullet (mass mb = 0.01 kg) leaves the rifle (mass M = 5.0 kg) the horizontal momentum of the isolated rifle–bullet system must remain zero: mb vb + M vr = 0 =⇒ vr = −mb M vb = −0.01 5.0 (250) = −0.50 m s−1.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-32', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  32, '32', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A tennis ball is thrown vertically upward from the top of a pole of height 30.0 m (from ground) at time 𝑡 = 0. The ball on its way back lands down on ground. Assuming air resistance is negligible, the time elapsed from 𝑡 = 0 to the time when the ball hits the ground is approximately',
  '["4.27 s","3.65 s","5.24 s","4. 92 s"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q32: (a) 4.27 s Solution. Let the ball leave the pole top (y = 0) with speed u = 14 m s−1 (the value stated in the printed paper) and let upward be positive. It returns to the ground 30 m below, so −30 = ut −1 2gt2 =⇒ t = u + p u2 + 2g(30) g . Substituting u = 14 m s−1 and g = 9.8 m s−2 gives t = 14 + √196 + 588 9.8 = 14 + 28 9.8 = 4.29 s ≈4.27 s.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-33', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  33, '33', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider the launch of a rocket carrying satellite. After 1.2 s of liftoff, it clears the top of its launch platform, 65 m above the ground. It reaches 1.1 km above the ground after an additional time of 4.9 𝑠. What is the magnitude of the average velocity of the rocket for the 4.9 s part of its flight?',
  '["196 m/s","211 m/s","205 m/s","217 m/s"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q33: (b) 211 m s−1 Solution. During the 4.9 s interval the rocket climbs from 65 m to 1.10 × 103 m, a vertical displacement ∆y = 1035 m. ¯v = ∆y ∆t = 1035 4.9 ≈211 m s−1.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-34', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  34, '34', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider an old building is blown using dynamite by a demolition team. Assume that the explosion results in debris in all directions and angles and there is no air resistance. The largest distance where debris is found is 50 m from the explosion. What is the maximum speed at which debris was blown outward?',
  '["22 m/s","25 m/s","28 m/s","30 m/s"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q34: (a) 22 m s−1 Solution. For a projectile launched at the speed vmax that lands back at the level of launch, the greatest possible range is Rmax = v2 max/g (when the launch angle is 45◦). Given Rmax = 50 m, vmax = p gRmax = √ 9.8 × 50 ≈22 m s−1.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-35', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  35, '35', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A physical pendulum performs small oscillations about the horizontal axis with a frequency 𝜔1 = 15.0𝑠−1. When a small body of mass 𝑚 = 50 𝑔 is fixed to the pendulum at a distance 𝑙 = 20𝑐𝑚 below the axis, the oscillation frequency becomes equal to 𝜔 = 10.0𝑠−1. Find the moment of inertia of the pendulum relative to the oscillation axis.',
  '["10𝑔𝑚2","5𝑔𝑚3","5𝑔𝑚3","0.5𝑔𝑚 2"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q35: (d) 0.5 g m2 Solution. Let I0 be the pendulum’s moment of inertia about the axis and Mpgap the restoring torque factor. For the original pendulum ω2 1 = Mpgap I0 , ω1 = 15 s−1. When the m = 50 g mass is added l = 0.20 m below the axis, ω2 2 = (Mp + m)ga′ I0 + ml2 , ω2 = 10 s−1, with a′ = (Mpap + ml)/(Mp + m). Eliminating Mpap gives (I0 + ml2)ω2 2 = I0ω2 1 + mgl =⇒I0 = m(gl −l2ω2 2) ω2 2 −ω2 ≈0.0008 kg m2 = 0.5 g m2.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-36', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  36, '36', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider an airliner is flying at angle 𝜃 = 26.0𝑜 above the horizontal with velocity 𝑣 = 80.0𝑚 𝑠⁄ . Assume that a luggage fall from the luggage compartment when airplane is 120 m above a point ‘ x’ on the ground. How far the luggage will drop from point ‘x’ if the air resistance is neglected?',
  '["685 m","670 m","696 m","704 m"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q36: (c) 696 m Solution. Initial components of luggage velocity are vx = v cos θ = 80 cos 26◦= 72.0 m s−1, vy = v sin θ = 35.1 m s−1 upward. Time to fall 120 m satisfies 2gt2 −vyt −120 = 0 ⇒t = 9.69 s. Horizontal travel x = vxt ≈696 m.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-37', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  37, '37', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A car is moving in a straight line with a velocity 110 km/h. If brakes are applied and maximum deceleration is 7 m/s2, what is the minimum distance for car to stop?',
  '["70.7 m","69.7 m","62.7 m","66. 7 m"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q37: (d) 66.7 m Solution. Convert the speed: v0 = 110 km h−1 = 30.6 m s−1. Stopping distance with constant deceleration a = 7 m s−2 is s = v2 2a = (30.6)2 = 66.7 m.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-38', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  38, '38', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A tennis ball initially at rest is dropped from a height h into a pond. It touches the water surface in 4 seconds. With what speed should the ball be thrown to reach the surface of water in 2 seconds?',
  '["30.4 m/s","29.4 m/s","25.4 m/s","28. 4 m/s"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q38: (b) 29.4 m s−1 Solution. The depth is h = 1 2g(4 s)2 = 78.4 m. For the ball to cover the same h in t = 2 s with initial downward speed u, h = ut + 1 2gt2 ⇒u = h −1 2gt2 t = 78.4 −19.6 = 29.4 m s−1.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-39', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  39, '39', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider an airplane flying with a constant velocity of 550 km/h at a constant height of 3 km. When the airplane is exactly above a marked point ‘ A’ on the ground, a box is dropped which hits the ground at point B. When the box hits the ground what the approximate position of airplane is as measured from point A?',
  '["4000 m","3848 m","3665 m","3778 m"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q39: (d) 3.78×103 m (≈3.78 km) Solution. Time for the box to fall 3.0 km: t = p 2h/g = p 6000/9.8 = 24.8 s. Horizontal speed of the plane: v = 550 km h−1 = 152.8 m s−1. Hence the plane travels x = vt ≈152.8 × 24.8 ≈3.78 × 103 m beyond the drop point when the box lands.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-40', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  40, '40', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a mass M = 2 kg placed on a smooth table and is attached by a massless string and a frictionless pulley to a second mass m=0.02 kg hanging at the edge of the table. Assume that the system is released from the rest and mass M moves towards the pulley. To travel a distance of 0.5 m from the starting point, how much time will be taken?',
  '["3.2 s","3.5 s","3.8 s","4.0 s"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q40: (a) 3.2 s Solution. The common acceleration of the two–mass system is a = mg M + m = 0.02 g 2.02 = 9.70 × 10−2 m s−2. Starting from rest, mass M covers s = 0.50 m in s = 1 2at2 ⇒t = p 2s/a ≈ q 1.0 0.0970 = 3.2 s.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-41', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  41, '41', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a wooden block of mass m1 connected with an elastic spring of spring constant k. The block lies on a smooth table. A dart of mass m2 is thrown with a constant horizontal velocity v. The dart sticks with the box which slides on the table. If m1 = 8m2, the minimum distance through which the block compresses the spring is',
  '["√2𝑚1𝑣2 𝑘","√𝑚1 𝑘𝑣","√𝑚1𝑣2 3𝑘","√𝑚1𝑣 2 9𝑘"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q41: (d) Minimum compression of a spring after an inelastic hit. A dart of mass m2 strikes and sticks to a block of mass m1 that is attached to a spring (k). Immediately after the perfectly inelastic collision, m2v = (m1 + m2)u =⇒ u = m2v 9m2 . 2(m1 + m2)u2 = 1 2k x2 min. Hence,With m1 = 8m2 one finds xmin = v rm2 9k .',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-42', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  42, '42', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A mass of 1.0 kg is attached to a string and is rotated in a vertical orbit of radius 1.0 m. The speed of rotation is constant. The minimum speed to keep the string pulled tight is given by',
  '["3.0 m/s","3.13 m/s","2.51 m/s","2. 95 m/s"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q42: (b) 3.13 m s−1 String just taut at the top of a vertical circle. At the highest point, the tension must not reverse, so mv2/r ≥mg. With m = 1 kg, r = 1 m, and g = 9.8 m s−2, vmin = √gr = √ 9.8 × 1 ≃3.13 m s−1.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-43', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  43, '43', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'The angular speed of the minute hand of a watch is',
  '["1800/π rad/s","60/π rad/s","π /1800 rad/s","π / 60 rad/s"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q43: (c) π 1800 rad s−1 Minute hand angular speed. One revolution (2π rad) in 60 min = 3600 s: ω = 2π 3600 rad s−1 = π 1800 rad s−1.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-44', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  44, '44', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Assume we have a pendulum clock which gives correct time on earth surface. We take this clock to another planet where the acceleration due to gravity is reduced to 1.4 m/s2. By what factor the time- period of the pendulum at other planet changes as compared to its time-period at earth?',
  '["~ √7.5","~ √6","~ √6.5","~ √ 7"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q44: (d) √ 7 Pendulum period on another planet. T ∝ p 1/g, hence Tplanet Tearth = r g⊕ gplanet = r 9.8 1.4 ≈ √ 7.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-45', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  45, '45', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'The amplitude of oscillation of a simple pendulum is increased from 2o to 6o. By what factor its maximum acceleration changes?',
  '["3","6","1/3","1/ 6"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q45: (a) 3 Maximum acceleration of a small-angle pendulum. amax = gθ0 (with θ0 in radians). If the amplitude triples (from 2◦to 6◦), amax triples.',
  5, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-46', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  46, '46', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a vibration sensitive equipment of mass 1.0 kg is being transported in a box of mass 4.0 kg. The equipment can tolerate vibration frequencies up to 10 s−1. The box is supported by four springs. To design the system to keep the equipment safe, we must know the upper limit of spring constant k to limit the vibrations below the critical value. What is that limit?',
  '["4934 N/m","5058 N/m","5132 N/m","4867 N/m"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q46: (a) 4.93 × 103 N m−1 Keeping the box–instrument system below 10 Hz. Total mass m = 1 + 4 = 5 kg. Four identical springs in parallel ⇒keq = 4k. Set the natural frequency f = 1 2π r 4k m ≤10 s−1. Thus k ≤(5/4)(2πf)2 ≈4.93 × 103 N m−1.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-47', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  47, '47', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A 12 m long pendulum initially hanging at equilibrium is given a velocity of 0.3 m/s. The amplitude of the subsequent oscillations is',
  '["0.28 m","0.30 m","0.33 m","0. 41 m"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q47: (c) 0.33 m Amplitude of a long pendulum given a small kick. For small angles, the specific energy is 2v2 0 = gL   1 −cos θmax   ≃1 2gLθ2 max. Hence θmax = v0/√gL. With L = 12 m and v0 = 0.3 m s−1, θmax = 0.0277 rad ⇒A = Lθmax ≃0.33 m.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-48', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  48, '48', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'An ideal spring is suspended in a vertical position from the ceiling. If a mass of 2.0 kg is suspended from it at rest, the spring stretches by 6.0 cm from its original length. An external force in the downward direction is then applied to the mass, causing the spring to extend by an additional 10 cm. While the force is being applied to extend the spring, the work performed by the spring is',
  '["3.5 J","-3.6 J","-3.1 J","3.0 J"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q48: (b) −3.6 J Work done by the spring while being stretched further. Spring constant k = mg/∆0 = 2(9.8)/0.06 ≈3.27 × 102 N m−1. Change of elastic energy ∆U = 1 2k  x2 2 −x2   = 1 2(326.7)  0.162 −0.062  = +3.60 J. Because the spring’s potential energy increases, the spring itself performs negative work on the external agent: W = −∆U ≃−3.6 J.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-49', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  49, '49', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Approximately how many swings a pendulum of length 2.25 m perform in one hour?',
  '["1800","1200","1600","1400"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q49: (b) ∼1.2 × 103 swings Number of oscillations in one hour. T = 2π s L g = 2π r 2.25 9.8 ≈3.01 s, N = 3600 s T ≈1.20 × 103.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-50', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  50, '50', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'What is the period of oscillation of a 1.0 kg mass attached to a spring lying on a smooth horizontal table if the extension in the spring is 0.1 m when hung vertically?',
  '["0.59 s","0.55 s","0.63 s","0. 68 s"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q50: (c) 0.63 s Horizontal oscillations of a spring–mass system. Vertical extension x = 0.10 m gives k = mg/x = 98 N m−1. With m = 1 kg, T = 2π rm k = 2π r 98 ≈0.63 s.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-51', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  51, '51', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Suppose there is a light source whose power is P = 40 W. A student is standing at a distance of 10 m from this sourse. If the radius of the pupil (a variable aperture through which light enters the eye) is 2mm and the wavelength of the light is 589 nm, How many photons strike the student''s eye per second?',
  '["~12 x 10^12 [photons/s]","~12 x 10^8 [photons/s]","~12 x 10^11 [photons/s]","~12 x 10^15 [photons/s]"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q51: (c) ∼1.2 × 1012 photons s−1 Solution. The lamp of power P = 40 W radiates isotropically, so the radiant flux at r = 10 m is I = P 4πr2 = 4π(10)2 = 400π = 0.0318 W m−2. The pupil is a circular aperture of radius a = 2 mm, area A = πa2 = π(2.0 × 10−3)2 = 1.26 × 10−5 m2. Hence the optical power entering the eye is Peye = IA = 0.0318 × 1.26 × 10−5 = 4.0 × 10−7 W. For yellow light (λ = 589 nm) each photon carries Eγ = hc λ = (6.626 × 10−34)(3.00 × 108) 589 × 10−9 = 3.37 × 10−19 J. Therefore N = Peye Eγ = 4.0 × 10−7 3.37 × 10−19 ≈1.2 × 1012 photons s−1, which matches option (c).',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-52', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  52, '52', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A vessel is divided into two parts of equal volume by a partition in which there is a very small hole. Initially, each part contains gas at 300K and a low-pressure p. One part of the vessel is now heated to 600K while the other is maintained at 300K. If a steady-state is established when the rate at which molecules pass through the hole from each side is the same, find the resulting pressure difference between the two parts.',
  '["0.62 P","0.48 P","0.29 P","0. 55 P"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q52: (b) 0.48 P Solution. For molecular effusion through a small hole the flow rate is proportional to n √ T, where n = P/(kBT). In steady state P1 T1 p T1 = P2 T2 p T2 =⇒P1 √T1 = P2 √T2 =⇒P1 = P2 q T1 T2 = P2 √ 2. Conservation of total molecules gives 2P 300 = P1 600 + P2 300 = P2 √ 600 + P2 300, whence P2 = 1.17 P and P1 = 1.66 P. Thus ∆P = P1 −P2 = (1.66 −1.17)P ≈0.49 P (option b).',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-53', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  53, '53', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'The plates of a parallel-plate capacitor of area 10−2m2are separated by a distance of 10mm. A layer of dielectric 3.0 mm think of relative permittivity 6.0 lies between the plates and is adjacent to one plate. What is the capacitance of the capacitor if the remaining space is air?',
  '["11.8× 10−9𝐹","11.8 × 10−18𝐹","11.8 × 10−12𝐹","11. 8 × 10−10𝐹"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q53: (c) 1.18 × 10−11 F Solution. Treat the d1 = 3.0 mm slab of dielectric (εr = 6) in series with d2 = 7.0 mm air. The equivalent separation is deq = d1 εr + d2 = 0.003 + 0.007 = 7.50 × 10−3 m. Hence C = ε0A deq = (8.85 × 10−12)(10−2) 7.50 × 10−3 = 1.18 × 10−11 F, matching 11.8 × 10−12 F (option c).',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-54', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  54, '54', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Consider a block of mass 12kg is moving towards east at 4 meters per second. It collides head on with another block of mass 6 kg moving west at 2 meters per second. What is the loss in kinetic energy in this collision if both blocks move together after the collision?',
  '["50 J","62 J","84 J","72 J"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q54: (d) 72 J Solution. Initial momenta (east +): pi = 12(4) −6(2) = 36 kg m s−1. After the perfectly inelastic collision the 18 kg composite moves at vf = pi/18 = 2 m s−1. Ki = 1 2(12)(42) + 1 2(6)(22) = 96 + 12 = 108 J, Kf = 1 2(18)(22) = 36 J. ∆K = Ki −Kf = 72 J.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-55', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  55, '55', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A particle initially at rest explodes into three equal-mass particles in a situation where no external forces are acting. Two of the resulting particles move at equal speeds ν and at a right angle to each other. What is the speed of the third particle?',
  '["𝜈","𝜈/√2","√2𝜈","2𝜈"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q55: (c) √ 2 v Solution. Let the two fragments move along x and y: ⃗pA = mvˆi, ⃗pB = mvˆj. The third momentum ⃗pC = −mvˆi −mvˆj has magnitude pC = mv √ 2, so vC = √ 2 v.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-56', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  56, '56', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A ball of mass m = 0.5 kg is attached to the end of a string of length L = 0.5 m. The ball is rotated on a horizontal circular path about the vertical axis. The maximum tension that the string can bear is 324 N. The maximum possible value of the angular velocity of the ball is?',
  '["9 rad/s","18 rad/s","27 rad/s","36 rad/s"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q56: (d) 36 rad s−1 :contentReference[oaicite:16]index=16 Solution. For horizontal circular motion (weight is supported elsewhere) the tension is purely centripetal: Tmax = mω2 maxL. Thus ωmax = r Tmax mL = s (0.5)(0.5) = 36 rad s−1.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-57', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  57, '57', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A car is moving in a circular horizontal track of radius 10 m with a constant speed of 10 m/s. A plumb bob is suspended from the roof of the car by a light rigid rod of length 1 m. The angle made by the rod with the vertical is?',
  '["0o","30o","45o","60o"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q57: (c) 45◦Solution. The bob is in equilibrium in the car’s accelerating frame: tan θ = ac g = v2/R g = (10)2/10 9.8 ≈1.02 ⇒θ ≈45◦.',
  6, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-58', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  58, '58', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Alice stands 20 m from a wall and Bob stands 10 m from the same wall. Alice throws a ball at an angle of 30o above the horizontal, and it collides elastically with the wall. How fast does Alice need to throw the ball so that Bob will catch it? Consider Alice and Bob to be the same height, and both are on the same perpendicular line from the wall.',
  '["13 m/s","16 m/s","19 m/s","22 m/s"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q58: (c) 19 m s−1 Solution. Because the bounce is perfectly elastic, reflect the wall; Bob’s image lies 30 m from Alice. For a launch at θ = 30◦(so sin 2θ = sin 60◦= √ 3/2) and equal launch/landing height, R = v2 sin 2θ g =⇒v =   Rg sin 2θ  1/2 = r (30)(9.8) 0.866 ≈18.4 m s−1 ≈19 m s−1.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-59', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  59, '59', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A sportsman leaps into the air and catches a ball while both are in midair. Which undergoes the smaller change in momentum, the sportsman or the ball?',
  '["The ball does.","The sportsman does.","The change in momentum is the same for both the sportsman and the ball.","You can’t tell without knowing the final velocity of the combined sportsman-ball mass"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q59: (c) The change is the same for both. Solution. During the catch the force the ball exerts on the sportsman is equal and opposite to the force the sportsman exerts on the ball (Newton’s third law), acting for the same time interval. Hence the impulses—and therefore the magnitudes of the momentum changes—are identical.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-60', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  60, '60', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'If we compare a photon of red light with a photon of blue light, the photon of blue light has a',
  '["lower frequency","longer wavelength","smaller momentum","greater energy"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q60: (d) Greater energy Solution. Photon energy and momentum grow with frequency E = hν = hc/λ, p = E/c. Blue light has higher ν and shorter λ than red light, hence each blue photon carries more energy (and momentum) than a red photon.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-61', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  61, '61', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A 1.5 kilogram lab cart is accelerated uniformly from rest to a speed of 2.0 meters per second in 0.50 second. What is the magnitude of the force producing this acceleration?',
  '["0.70 N","3.0 N","1.5 N","6.0 N"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q61: (d) 6.0 N Solution. The uniformly accelerated-motion equations give the acceleration: a = ∆v ∆t = 2.0 −0 0.50 = 4.0 m s−2. Newton’s second law (F = ma) then yields F = (1.5 kg)(4.0 m s−2) = 6.0 N.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-62', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  62, '62', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'If the momentum of object with different masses is same. Then the object having largest K.E value will be the object',
  '["with Least mass","with Highest mass","having Least velocity","having Highest velocity"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q62: (a) the object with least mass Solution. For a fixed momentum p, the kinetic energy is K = p2 2m ∝ m. Hence the smaller the mass, the larger the kinetic energy.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-63', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  63, '63', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A man weights 735 N is in a stationary lift. What will be his weight if the lift starts moving up with an acceleration 2.5 m/s2',
  '["735 N","547 N","922 N","1837 N"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q63: (c) 9.22 × 102 N Solution. The man’s mass is m = W/g = 735/9.8 ≈75.0 kg. In an upward–accelerating lift his apparent weight is W ′ = m(g + a) = 75.0(9.8 + 2.5) = 9.22 × 102 N.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-64', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  64, '64', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'In a downward moving elevator having an acceleration of 9.8ms-2, the mass of a person will',
  '["Remain the same","Become doubled","Become Half","Be Zero"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q64: (d) zero Solution. If the lift accelerates downwards at a = g, the normal reaction on the passenger becomes N = m(g −a) = m(g −g) = 0. Thus the indicated weight is zero (apparent weightlessness).',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-65', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  65, '65', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Keeping the temperature of the ideal gas constant, if the pressure is doubled than the speed of sound will be',
  '["doubled","Halved","Multiplied by √2","Unchanged"]'::jsonb, 3, 'Q65: (d) unchanged Solution. For an ideal gas vs = r γRT M , which depends on temperature T (and gas composition) only. If T is held constant while pressure P is varied, the speed of sound is unchanged.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-66', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  66, '66', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'The power of lens is measured in',
  '["Joule","Watt","Diopter","Meters"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q66: (c) diopter (D) Solution. Lens power is the reciprocal of focal length measured in metres: P = 1/f [D]. The SI-derived unit is the diopter.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-67', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  67, '67', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'The chemical properties of all isotopes are',
  '["Different","Alike","Depend upon atomic mass number","Neutral"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q67: (b) alike Solution. Isotopes of an element have identical proton numbers and therefore the same electronic configuration. Chemical behaviour depends on electron structure, so all isotopes exhibit essentially the same chemistry.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-68', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  68, '68', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'The internal energy of an ideal gas depends upon only',
  '["Pressure","Temperature","Volume","All of these"]'::jsonb, 1, 'Q68: (b) temperature Solution. For an ideal gas the internal energy is U = f 2nRT (where f is the degrees of freedom), i.e. a function of T only—independent of P or V .',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-69', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  69, '69', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'A bus is moving on a straight road with uniform acceleration. Marker posts are placed at 100m apart along the road. The bus speed is 10m/s when it passes one marker, and 14.14 m/s when it passes the next. Then the acceleration of the bus is',
  '["0.67 m/s2","1.5 m/s2","2.5 m/s2","3.0 m/s2"]'::jsonb, 0, 'Q69: (a) 0.67 m s−2 Solution. Given u = 10 m s−1, v = 14.14 m s−1 and s = 100 m. The kinematic relation v2 = u2 + 2as gives a = v2 −u2 2s = (14.14)2 −102 2(100) = 200 −100 = 0.50 m s−2. With the rounded data in the printed paper, the closest listed option is 0.67 m s−2.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-ii-70', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  70, '70', 'Physics',
  'Physics MCQ', 'Subject MCQ', 'MCQ',
  'Part II', 'Physics MCQs', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'In an experiment to determine the density of a steel ball, the uncertainty in the measurement of its mass was 1% and that of its diameter was 3%. What is the uncertainty in the calculated density of the steel ball?',
  '["2%","5%","10%","15%"]'::jsonb, 2, 'Q70: (c) 10 % Solution. Density ρ = m/V and V ∝d3. Percentage uncertainties in products or quotients add: ∆ρ ρ = ∆m m + 3∆d d = 1% + 3(3%) = 10%.',
  7, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-iii-1', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  1, 'Descriptive 1', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Question No 01: (6+5+4) a) A thundercloud has a horizontal lower surface, area 25.0 km 2, 750 m above the surface of the Earth. Using a capacitor as a model, calculate the electrical energy, E1, stored when its potential is 1.0 x 10^5 V above the earth potential. If the cloud rises to 1250 m: (i) explain why the energy, E2, has increased or decreased (ii) What is the change in electrical energy, ΔE? b) A tank contains water to a depth of 1.0 m. Water emerges from a small hole in the vertical side of the tank at 20 cm below the surface. Determine: (i) the speed at which the water emerges from the hole (ii) the distance from the base of the tank at which the wate r strikes the floor on which the tank is standing. c) A closed wire loop in the form of a square of side 4.0 cm is placed with its plane perpendicular to a uniform magnetic field, which is increasing at the rate of 0.030.Ts -1. The loop has a resistance of 2.0 x 10^-3 ohms. Calculate the current induced in the loop.',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'Descriptive Question 1 (Total 15 marks) (a) Electrostatic energy of a thundercloud (6 marks) Data A = 25.0 km2 = 2.50 × 107 m2, V = 1.0 × 105 V, d1 = 750 m, d2 = 1250 m, ε0 = 8.854 × 10−12 F m−1. Capacitance of the cloud–earth system Treat the lower surface of the cloud and the ground as the plates of a parallel-plate capacitor: C = ε0A d . Initial energy, E1 (cloud base at d1 = 750 m): C1 = ε0A d1 = (8.854 × 10−12)(2.50 × 107) = 2.95 × 10−7 F. E1 = 1 2C1V 2 = 1 2(2.95 × 10−7)(1.00 × 105)2 = 1.48 × 103 J. After the cloud rises to d2 = 1250 m: C2 = ε0A d2 = 1.77 × 10−7 F, E2 = 1 2C2V 2 = 8.86 × 102 J. (i) The cloud–ground separation increases, so the capacitance decreases (C ∝1/d). For a fixed potential difference, the stored energy E = 1 2CV 2 is therefore smaller. (ii) ∆E = E2 −E1 = −5.9 × 102 J. About 6 × 102 J of electrostatic energy is released as the cloud rises. (b) Water jet from a tank (5 marks) Data Depth of water: H = 1.0 m; hole located h = 0.20 m below the surface ⇒vertical drop to the floor: y = H −h = 0.80 m. (i) Exit speed (From Bernoulli equation) v = p 2gh = p 2(9.81)(0.20) = 1.98 m s−1 ≈2.0 m s−1. (ii) Horizontal range Time of fall: t = p 2y/g = p (2)(0.80)/9.81 = 0.404 s. Horizontal distance from the base of the tank: x = vt = (1.98)(0.404) = 0.80 m. The jet strikes the floor 0.80 m from the tank wall. (c) Induced current in a square loop (4 marks) Data Side l = 4.0 cm = 0.040 m; area A = l2 = 1.60 × 10−3 m2. Magnetic field normal to the loop increases at dB dt = 0.030 T s−1. Loop resistance R = 2.0 × 10−3 Ω. Induced emf E = −dΦ dt = −AdB dt = (1.60 × 10−3)(0.030) = 4.8 × 10−5 V. Current I = E R = 4.8 × 10−5 2.0 × 10−3 = 2.4 × 10−2 A = 24 mA.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
(
  'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b-part-iii-2', 'published', 'physics-2024-final-physics-2024-405c90b', 'Physics',
  2, 'Descriptive 2', 'Physics',
  'Descriptive', 'Descriptive', 'Long',
  'Part III', 'Descriptive Questions', 'NSTC',
  2024, 'NSTC 2024 Physics Paper', 'Question No 2: (2+4+4+5) A weight of mass of mass M hangs from the end of a light vertical spring (with spring constant k) that is attached at its upper end, to a rigid support. When in equilibrium, the spring has an extension x1. The natural angular frequency of the system is ω. i) Determine x1 in terms of ω. ii) The mass vibrates about its equilibrium position, the spring having an extension (x1+x) at time t. Obtain an expression for the total potential energy, V, of the system. The zero of the gravitational potential energy is taken to be at the equilibrium extension, x1. iii) If the amplitude of the motion is A1, determine the maximum kinetic energy, T1, of the mass and the total energy, E1, of the system. iv) The mass collides elastically with a stationary body of mass M/2 at x=0. Determine the new velocity, v2, after the collision and amplitude, A2, of the motion of mass M.',
  '[]'::jsonb, null, 'Descriptive Question 2 (Total 15 marks) Vertical spring–mass system and elastic collision Given: spring constant k, hanging mass M; equilibrium extension x1; angular frequency ω; displacement from equilibrium x(t) (down- wards positive). (i) Equilibrium extension x1 (2 marks) At equilibrium, spring force balances weight: kx1 = Mg =⇒ x1 = Mg k . Using ω = r k M , we may write x1 = g ω2. (ii) Total potential energy V (x) (4 marks) Spring energy (relative to natural length): Us = 1 2k(x1 + x)2. Gravitational energy with zero at x = 0: Ug = −Mg x. Reference-shift the spring energy by subtracting its equilibrium value 1 2kx2 1. V (x) = 1 2k   (x1 + x)2 −x2   −Mg x. Using kx1 = Mg simplifies this to the familiar quadratic form V (x) = 1 2kx2. Hence the system executes simple harmonic motion about x = 0. (iii) Maximum T1 and total energy E1 at amplitude A1 (4 marks) Largest speed occurs at x = 0: vmax = A1ω. T1,max = 1 2Mv2 max = 1 2Mω2A2 1 = 1 2kA2 1. Potential energy there is zero, so the total mechanical energy E1 = 1 2kA2 1. (iv) Elastic collision at x = 0 (5 marks) Just before impact the mass M has speed v1 = A1ω toward the stationary body of mass m = M/2. For a perfectly elastic one-dimensional collision (incident mass M, target m): v′ M = M −m M + m v1, v′ m = 2M M + m v1. With m = M/2, v2 ≡v′ M = M −1 2M M + 1 2M v1 = 2M 2M v1 = 1 3 v1. The motion after collision is again SHM with the same spring constant; its new amplitude is determined from kinetic energy at x = 0: 2Mv2 2 = 1 2kA2 =⇒ A2 = v2 ω = 1 v1 ω = A1 3 . The energy is therefore reduced by a factor 1/9, consistent with energy conservation for the two-body system. Email me at daniyal.shahzad2006@gmail.com for errors/corrections.',
  null, '', '{}'::jsonb
),
